WEBVTT

00:01.251 --> 00:09.092
♪

00:14.431 --> 00:20.020
♪

00:20.020 --> 00:21.813
The success of
the James Bond films

00:21.813 --> 00:25.317
has made household names
out of actors playing Agent 007.

00:25.317 --> 00:26.276
Bond.

00:26.276 --> 00:27.778
The name's Bond.

00:27.778 --> 00:28.987
James Bond.

00:28.987 --> 00:30.822
Except for one.

00:30.822 --> 00:32.573
The forgotten James Bond.

00:32.573 --> 00:40.499
♪

00:40.499 --> 00:42.793
George Lazenby went from
being a car salesman

00:42.793 --> 00:44.753
in Queanbeyan in the 1960s

00:44.753 --> 00:46.338
to playing 007.

00:46.338 --> 00:49.258
Is it true that, as I think
you put it yourself once,

00:49.258 --> 00:52.135
you told a pack of
lies to get the role?

00:52.135 --> 01:03.647
♪

01:03.647 --> 01:05.190
And now it's our great joy

01:05.190 --> 01:07.985
to welcome the new James Bond.

01:07.985 --> 01:20.205
♪

01:20.205 --> 01:21.957
Now this is a fascinating
situation, isn't it?

01:21.957 --> 01:22.916
Because you've, what,

01:22.916 --> 01:26.086
you've refused
to do a second Bond?

01:26.086 --> 01:45.856
♪

01:45.856 --> 01:47.441
(light clicks)

01:49.026 --> 01:50.902
So you're gonna
tell me your story.

01:50.902 --> 01:53.196
I'm wondering what
can I expect from it?

01:53.196 --> 01:54.239
Drama?

01:54.239 --> 01:55.699
Do I have drama about what?

01:55.699 --> 01:57.993
In your life story
that I'm gonna ask you.

01:57.993 --> 02:00.412
Is there drama?

02:00.412 --> 02:01.788
What do you mean
"is there drama"?

02:01.788 --> 02:04.875
-There's drama all my life.
-Is there romance?

02:04.875 --> 02:06.418
-Huh, yes.
-Is there romance?

02:06.418 --> 02:08.502
-Is there comedy?
-Yes.

02:08.502 --> 02:10.213
Sex?

02:10.213 --> 02:11.256
A little.

02:11.256 --> 02:12.507
Drugs?

02:12.507 --> 02:13.759
Drugs, yeah, a little.

02:13.759 --> 02:15.594
-Violence?
-A little.

02:15.594 --> 02:17.262
Are there twists and turns?

02:17.262 --> 02:20.265
-Yes.
-Is it a good story?

02:20.265 --> 02:22.684
Oh, well, it depends

02:22.684 --> 02:26.188
if you like those
kind of stories, you know?

02:26.188 --> 02:33.779
♪

02:33.779 --> 02:36.907
Well, it all started, my life,

02:36.907 --> 02:38.617
from what I remember,

02:38.617 --> 02:39.951
being in hospital.

02:39.951 --> 02:41.078
Scalpel.

02:41.078 --> 02:43.413
♪

02:43.413 --> 02:44.539
Hold that, hold that.

02:44.539 --> 02:46.208
When I was three years old...

02:46.208 --> 02:48.418
Oh shit, he's awake!

02:48.418 --> 02:52.381
Shh, go back to sleep.

02:52.381 --> 02:54.466
...they found that
I was peeing backwards

02:54.466 --> 02:55.801
into my kidneys.

02:55.801 --> 02:56.802
♪

02:56.802 --> 02:59.596
They opened me up 67 times.

02:59.596 --> 03:01.139
I was left with half a kidney.

03:01.139 --> 03:02.641
♪

03:02.641 --> 03:05.727
My doctors told my mother
that I'd probably pass away

03:05.727 --> 03:07.104
around 12.

03:07.104 --> 03:08.438
♪

03:08.438 --> 03:09.815
Maybe 13.

03:09.815 --> 03:11.233
I suppose, subconsciously,

03:11.233 --> 03:14.152
there was a part of me that
said I better get on with life

03:14.152 --> 03:15.696
because who knows?

03:15.696 --> 03:17.739
It could be over any time.

03:17.739 --> 03:22.119
♪

03:22.119 --> 03:23.829
The first time
I ever stole a car

03:23.829 --> 03:25.163
I was six years old.

03:25.163 --> 03:26.081
♪

03:26.081 --> 03:27.374
I think I said to myself,

03:27.374 --> 03:30.085
"I better make the best
of the time that I do have."

03:30.085 --> 03:31.236
♪

03:33.004 --> 03:34.423
And my dad never had a car

03:34.423 --> 03:36.466
because we were
a poor family.

03:36.466 --> 03:39.177
But my uncle used to
drive a '36 Ford.

03:39.177 --> 03:41.847
And I mean, I loved that thing.

03:41.847 --> 03:44.015
He'd always left
his keys in it.

03:44.015 --> 03:45.016
Crikey.

03:45.016 --> 03:47.269
And I had to get
underneath the dashboard...

03:47.269 --> 03:49.855
(engine roars to life)

03:49.855 --> 03:51.273
♪

03:51.273 --> 03:52.732
...and then I'd stand up

03:52.732 --> 03:54.234
and let the clutch out.

03:54.234 --> 03:55.861
♪

03:55.861 --> 03:57.487
Then it would kangaroo hop.

03:57.487 --> 04:02.951
♪

04:02.951 --> 04:04.161
(horn honks)

04:04.161 --> 04:08.999
♪

04:08.999 --> 04:10.333
That's how it was.

04:10.333 --> 04:12.377
♪

04:12.377 --> 04:14.671
I was a larrikin.

04:14.671 --> 04:16.839
I was a wild larrikin

04:16.839 --> 04:18.341
doing whatever I liked

04:18.341 --> 04:20.635
and I'd been that way forever.

04:20.635 --> 04:21.720
(school bell rings)

04:21.720 --> 04:24.181
Hurry up, kids,
take your seats.

04:24.181 --> 04:25.474
Settle down.

04:25.474 --> 04:26.683
Pencils out.

04:26.683 --> 04:27.893
♪

04:27.893 --> 04:29.603
So, as I was saying,

04:29.603 --> 04:31.146
science is all around--

04:31.146 --> 04:33.774
Yeah, no one expected
much of anything from me.

04:33.774 --> 04:34.900
George.

04:34.900 --> 04:36.067
Pay attention!

04:36.067 --> 04:38.028
I didn't see
the point in school.

04:38.028 --> 04:40.614
So this island here
is where we live.

04:40.614 --> 04:42.157
School was so boring.

04:42.157 --> 04:43.575
So boring.

04:43.575 --> 04:44.868
You know, it was, like,

04:44.868 --> 04:46.787
"God, I gotta learn
this geography thing."

04:46.787 --> 04:50.749
China and Russia
and Hungary and the Ukraine.

04:50.749 --> 04:53.376
I had no use knowing
where England was

04:53.376 --> 04:54.753
or where America was,

04:54.753 --> 04:55.962
I was in Australia

04:55.962 --> 04:57.005
and I wasn't going there.

04:57.005 --> 04:58.507
And the largest
clouds are called

04:58.507 --> 05:00.425
the cumulonimbus clouds.

05:00.425 --> 05:04.179
Science, who gives
a shit about science?

05:04.179 --> 05:05.722
Yes, what is it, George?

05:05.722 --> 05:08.517
Is this gonna be
relevant to my life?

05:08.517 --> 05:09.976
♪

05:09.976 --> 05:12.687
You know,
that was my attitude.

05:12.687 --> 05:16.107
George Lazenby,
outside right now.

05:16.107 --> 05:19.236
♪

05:19.236 --> 05:21.905
The vice headmaster,
Chook Warner.

05:21.905 --> 05:23.114
He hated me.

05:23.114 --> 05:24.241
♪

05:24.241 --> 05:27.327
Now, put out
your hands palms down.

05:27.327 --> 05:29.663
He would cane me
for no reason frankly.

05:29.663 --> 05:31.206
Quickly now.

05:31.206 --> 05:32.457
"Who did this?

05:32.457 --> 05:34.334
Who brought the snake to school?

05:34.334 --> 05:35.502
I bet you Lazenby did it.

05:35.502 --> 05:36.795
Come out outside."

05:36.795 --> 05:39.214
Because I did and I brought
a snake to school one day.

05:39.214 --> 05:47.055
♪

05:47.055 --> 05:50.851
I had to find ways to get
me through the day, you know?

05:50.851 --> 05:54.312
Like possibly causing
a little bit of trouble.

05:54.312 --> 05:56.815
The sun and it's all
part of the life cycle--

05:56.815 --> 05:58.316
One girl noticed it.

05:58.316 --> 06:00.694
(screaming)

06:00.694 --> 06:02.487
Wasn't gonna hurt anyone.

06:02.487 --> 06:05.240
Another day I brought
a bag full of bats.

06:05.240 --> 06:06.783
Time for school, bats!

06:06.783 --> 06:07.826
I went down the sewers

06:07.826 --> 06:10.245
and got a whole
bag full of bats.

06:10.245 --> 06:12.163
I put them in my school bag

06:12.163 --> 06:13.707
and then I opened the bag

06:13.707 --> 06:16.001
and they flew in the daylight.

06:16.001 --> 06:17.502
It was so much fun.

06:17.502 --> 06:19.713
People screaming, yelling,
and running everywhere.

06:19.713 --> 06:22.757
Children, try to remain calm!

06:22.757 --> 06:23.967
(chuckling)

06:23.967 --> 06:26.344
It was worth getting
the cane that day.

06:26.344 --> 06:30.140
(engine revving)

06:30.140 --> 06:35.562
♪

06:35.562 --> 06:37.022
You know,
to be honest with you,

06:37.022 --> 06:38.189
the things I was interested in

06:38.189 --> 06:40.275
were pranks and having fun.

06:40.275 --> 06:42.319
But when I turned 15,

06:42.319 --> 06:43.737
things changed.

06:43.737 --> 06:44.905
I can remember one morning

06:44.905 --> 06:46.781
riding down the hill on my bike,

06:46.781 --> 06:49.701
there was a girl
sunbaking on the lawn

06:49.701 --> 06:51.494
around the corner
from my place.

06:51.494 --> 06:52.454
♪

06:52.454 --> 06:53.913
June Green.

06:53.913 --> 06:57.542
She was 23 and I was 15.

06:57.542 --> 06:59.628
She had a fascinating body.

06:59.628 --> 07:00.629
♪

07:00.629 --> 07:01.713
So I stopped the bike

07:01.713 --> 07:03.548
and pretended something
was wrong with it.

07:03.548 --> 07:06.968
Okay, what is the problem here?

07:06.968 --> 07:08.720
Tire pressure seems fine.

07:08.720 --> 07:11.222
-I was fiddling with it...
-Might be the gas cap.

07:11.222 --> 07:13.266
...you know, and looking at it.

07:13.266 --> 07:16.061
I had no idea how to
approach a girl at that time.

07:16.061 --> 07:18.188
Might be this thing here.

07:18.188 --> 07:19.189
♪

07:19.189 --> 07:20.357
And she finally said,

07:20.357 --> 07:22.359
"What are you looking at?"

07:22.359 --> 07:24.444
And I said, "Oh,
my bike's broken down."

07:24.444 --> 07:27.113
Um, my bike's broken down.

07:27.113 --> 07:28.573
Uh...

07:28.573 --> 07:31.242
can I come in,
you got any tools?

07:31.242 --> 07:32.869
♪

07:32.869 --> 07:34.579
Yeah, okay.

07:34.579 --> 07:35.830
(tools clattering)

07:35.830 --> 07:36.790
♪

07:36.790 --> 07:39.668
Next thing I know,
I'm on top of her.

07:39.668 --> 07:41.586
This is fun.

07:41.586 --> 07:42.671
Yeah?

07:42.671 --> 07:43.963
Oh yeah, okay.

07:43.963 --> 07:46.174
-Okay.
-Cool.

07:46.174 --> 07:48.093
-Is that right?
-And we were dry rooting

07:48.093 --> 07:49.719
on the kitchen floor.

07:49.719 --> 07:51.262
Wait, what's dry rooting?

07:51.262 --> 07:54.307
That's doing it
with your clothes on.

07:54.307 --> 07:55.350
♪

07:55.350 --> 07:58.937
My arms are starting
to get tired a little bit.

07:58.937 --> 08:00.480
I had no idea what I was doing.

08:00.480 --> 08:03.024
-You okay?
-Uh, uh, my pants

08:03.024 --> 08:05.318
are bunching up a little bit.

08:05.318 --> 08:08.279
Eventually, she invited
me down at night.

08:08.279 --> 08:09.656
All right.

08:09.656 --> 08:13.034
And I can remember when we
made love for the first time.

08:13.034 --> 08:15.120
♪

08:15.120 --> 08:16.621
And it was fantastic.

08:16.621 --> 08:17.831
♪

08:17.831 --> 08:20.500
And all of a sudden
something took over my body.

08:20.500 --> 08:22.127
♪

08:22.127 --> 08:25.171
I was, like, in space
and it was magnificent.

08:25.171 --> 08:27.006
The best feeling
I've ever had in my life.

08:27.006 --> 08:29.300
(explosion)

08:35.597 --> 08:37.933
-I went, "Holy shit."
-Holy shit.

08:37.933 --> 08:39.059
What?

08:39.059 --> 08:41.520
I thought I'd blown
my penis apart.

08:42.605 --> 08:44.315
I got out of the car

08:44.315 --> 08:45.817
and struck a match
and checked it out

08:45.817 --> 08:48.737
to see everything
was still there.

08:48.737 --> 08:50.488
♪

08:50.488 --> 08:51.865
Are you okay?

08:51.865 --> 08:54.325
Yeah, we're good.

08:54.325 --> 08:56.453
My penis is fine.

08:56.453 --> 08:58.830
And then I couldn't wait
to get back in the car

08:58.830 --> 09:00.707
and have another one.

09:00.707 --> 09:03.793
I ended up going down
to her place every night.

09:03.793 --> 09:05.503
Why isn't everyone
doing this all the time?

09:05.503 --> 09:06.838
-Shut up!
-Okay.

09:06.838 --> 09:09.591
Until the school teacher
wrote a letter to my family

09:09.591 --> 09:12.510
that I couldn't keep
my eyes open during class.

09:12.510 --> 09:13.428
♪

09:13.428 --> 09:14.888
Michelle Cunningham.

09:14.888 --> 09:16.473
(applause)

09:16.473 --> 09:17.807
Michael Dickens.

09:17.807 --> 09:19.225
Well, there's a hall
in Queanbeyan

09:19.225 --> 09:20.727
called the Masonic Hall

09:20.727 --> 09:23.021
and that's where
all the kids go

09:23.021 --> 09:25.023
to graduate high school

09:25.023 --> 09:26.900
and you get an
intermediate certificate.

09:26.900 --> 09:28.234
Sarah Kinsworth.

09:28.234 --> 09:29.903
My mother came with me

09:29.903 --> 09:32.030
and I thought it's a given,

09:32.030 --> 09:33.114
everybody was getting one.

09:33.114 --> 09:34.365
Brendan O'Connor.

09:34.365 --> 09:36.242
Very rarely
someone doesn't get

09:36.242 --> 09:37.368
an intermediate certification.

09:37.368 --> 09:40.914
Andrew Lange.

09:40.914 --> 09:43.166
Finally, after about an hour...

09:43.166 --> 09:46.044
And George Lazenby...

09:46.044 --> 09:47.378
did not graduate.

09:47.378 --> 09:50.423
To the 1954 class of Goulburn,

09:50.423 --> 09:53.176
congratulations
and farewell.

09:53.176 --> 09:55.095
♪

09:55.095 --> 09:57.055
I was the only one
in the whole hall

09:57.055 --> 09:58.723
that didn't get a certificate.

09:58.723 --> 10:00.725
♪

10:00.725 --> 10:02.769
I'm thinking, "Jesus,

10:02.769 --> 10:04.729
couldn't even get
an intermediate certificate."

10:04.729 --> 10:05.855
♪

10:05.855 --> 10:08.441
I mean, I knew I wasn't
gonna be a public servant

10:08.441 --> 10:10.401
or a lawyer or a doctor

10:10.401 --> 10:13.488
or anywhere I thought
you might need an education.

10:13.488 --> 10:15.782
♪

10:15.782 --> 10:17.242
It's embarrassing.

10:17.242 --> 10:19.160
I didn't give a damn
about the certificate

10:19.160 --> 10:21.579
but it was the embarrassment
of not getting one

10:21.579 --> 10:23.039
that was hurting.

10:23.039 --> 10:29.003
♪

10:29.003 --> 10:30.296
If you didn't
graduate high school,

10:30.296 --> 10:34.217
you had to redo the same
class over again for a year.

10:34.217 --> 10:35.927
And I wasn't about to do that.

10:35.927 --> 10:39.806
So my uncle helped me out
and got me a job as a mechanic.

10:41.432 --> 10:43.351
There was no money in it.

10:43.351 --> 10:46.187
I got paid very poorly.

10:46.187 --> 10:47.438
Look at this thing.

10:47.438 --> 10:49.357
You're gonna look amazing
going down the street in it.

10:49.357 --> 10:51.609
Imagine it; here,
come on, sit down, sit down.

10:51.609 --> 10:55.238
Look, you can
look out at the stars...

10:55.238 --> 10:57.448
And one day, I saw
the car salesmen

10:57.448 --> 10:59.617
were having much more fun
than us mechanics.

10:59.617 --> 11:01.119
Mount myself on this hood,

11:01.119 --> 11:02.620
then I'll mount you
on the hood.

11:02.620 --> 11:03.997
I'd look out from
underneath the car

11:03.997 --> 11:06.499
and I'd see the guys
chatting up the girls and...

11:06.499 --> 11:07.876
Of course I come with the car.

11:07.876 --> 11:10.670
I can come, I can sit in the
backseat the entire time.

11:10.670 --> 11:13.131
We can both sit in
the backseat if you'd like.

11:13.131 --> 11:14.716
...going to work in a suit,

11:14.716 --> 11:16.634
going to nice places for lunch,

11:16.634 --> 11:18.344
you know, having
a car to drive

11:18.344 --> 11:20.513
-and I'm thinking...
-What am I doing under here?

11:20.513 --> 11:23.224
♪

11:23.224 --> 11:24.517
So I said to the boss,

11:24.517 --> 11:25.977
"I want to be a car salesman."

11:25.977 --> 11:28.479
♪

11:28.479 --> 11:31.482
But then I couldn't
sell anything.

11:31.482 --> 11:33.318
No, I saw this
old girl in the shop

11:33.318 --> 11:34.903
and worked on her
more than most actually

11:34.903 --> 11:37.322
but, um, fair bit
of room in the back.

11:37.322 --> 11:39.032
I can tell you like that.

11:39.032 --> 11:42.577
And, uh, you guys up to date
with your tetanus shots?

11:42.577 --> 11:44.245
I would, I'd get
ahead of the game there.

11:44.245 --> 11:45.288
Look on the bright side,

11:45.288 --> 11:46.748
it comes in a bunch
of different colors.

11:46.748 --> 11:49.500
-What do you say?
-I don't think so.

11:49.500 --> 11:50.710
Yeah.

11:50.710 --> 11:52.879
Yeah, you don't want to rush
into a decision like this

11:52.879 --> 11:55.840
but, um, I'll be here
if you change your mind.

11:55.840 --> 11:57.759
♪

11:57.759 --> 11:59.302
I was hopeless.

11:59.302 --> 12:01.304
I couldn't sell a bloody car.

12:01.304 --> 12:02.764
♪

12:02.764 --> 12:04.307
Comes in a few different colors.

12:04.307 --> 12:05.350
♪

12:05.350 --> 12:07.936
One guy there
who'd come out of university,

12:07.936 --> 12:09.854
-Johnny Horton.
-It's all yours!

12:09.854 --> 12:11.689
Here's the keys.

12:11.689 --> 12:13.733
Congratulations, beautiful!

12:13.733 --> 12:15.193
He was selling
30 a month

12:15.193 --> 12:16.319
and he knew nothing about cars.

12:16.319 --> 12:17.862
Don't forget to
tell your friends,

12:17.862 --> 12:19.197
Johnny Horton.

12:19.197 --> 12:21.699
♪

12:21.699 --> 12:23.534
(gunshots)

12:23.534 --> 12:25.245
(blows softly)

12:25.245 --> 12:26.746
(musical flourish)

12:26.746 --> 12:29.582
That used to piss me off.

12:29.582 --> 12:30.875
Oh, shit.

12:30.875 --> 12:34.045
Finally, the boss had an idea.

12:34.045 --> 12:35.380
He sent me down to Melbourne

12:35.380 --> 12:40.343
to a "How To Win Friends
and Influence People" course.

12:40.343 --> 12:42.553
And the only thing
I can remember learning

12:42.553 --> 12:44.597
was "Listen, don't talk."

12:44.597 --> 12:47.392
Listen to them,
see what they're interested in,

12:47.392 --> 12:49.227
and then only talk about that.

12:49.227 --> 12:50.645
Don't bother with the car.

12:50.645 --> 12:53.189
Listen, don't talk.

12:53.189 --> 12:54.857
I started listening
to the customers...

12:54.857 --> 12:56.067
So anyway, I was
saying to my friend,

12:56.067 --> 12:57.235
it's gotta be the other leg

12:57.235 --> 12:58.236
but then Rhonda says to me,

12:58.236 --> 12:59.404
"What about the paintings?"

12:59.404 --> 13:00.780
And then suddenly
I realized

13:00.780 --> 13:03.283
I'm totally out of gas
and my pet turtle Shelly

13:03.283 --> 13:04.909
needs to use the toilet.

13:04.909 --> 13:06.077
Anyways, I'll take that one.

13:06.077 --> 13:07.954
So, Shelly, she's in a mood.

13:07.954 --> 13:10.081
One time she almost
took off my pinky finger.

13:10.081 --> 13:11.082
But you know what?

13:11.082 --> 13:13.001
Pulled it back,
gave her a carrot,

13:13.001 --> 13:14.085
all was well.

13:14.085 --> 13:15.253
(laughing)

13:15.253 --> 13:16.879
God, what a twist.

13:16.879 --> 13:18.214
(laughing)

13:18.214 --> 13:19.924
My sales went up to 30 a month.

13:19.924 --> 13:21.175
Excellent choice, sir.

13:21.175 --> 13:22.802
